snippet.textDisplay:
Even though there are no "backdoors" in Huawei currently in their equipment, the fact that they can easily create and impliment a backdoor down the line with a simple automatic firmware/software upgrade push is the #1 reason why any nation should not accept equipment for vital infrastructure use from another nation they aren't allied with or fully trust. 

So if down the road China decided to go to war with a nation/region that has Huawei made equipment all over, they can force Huawei to push a firmware update that will either destroy/takedown and cripple the nation's infrastructure, or open the doors wide open for Chinese infiltration/cyberattack right before their physical armies invade. As a result, it's never a good idea, regardless if the company promises to not have any backdoors and allow external supervision, as all it takes is for the Chinese Government/Military to force the company to push a backdoor hidden in the guise of a firmware/software update...


...and since the update is coming from the product creator itself, the product will willingly accept these malicious updates or if updates are rolled out manually, IT employees may not scrutinize, question, or delve into any updates provided from the product company itself.
